{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491212"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:37:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:37:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"869"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/869"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.07,0.15,0.08,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"869"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76886"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/869"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"869"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62391"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"948"},{"type":"tags","id":"6087"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6325"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6866"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26474"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76886"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with difficulty using his left hand. He reports progressive weakness of grip when picking up farm implements. He experiences tingling in his little finger that worsens with gripping objects. He has difficulty pinching with his thumb and forefinger. He works as a farmhand and has no significant medical history apart from a traumatic left medial epicondyle fracture several years ago while working on a harvester. He takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His left hand shows clawing of the ring and little fingers with hyperextension at the metacarpophalangeal joints and flexion at the interphalangeal joints (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is most likely affected?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ulnar nerve","Radial nerve","Median nerve","Anterior interosseous nerve","Posterior interosseous nerve"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of ulnar nerve palsy, including clawing of the ring and little fingers, sensory changes in the ulnar distribution, and weakness of grip. The history of medial epicondyle fracture is significant as this commonly leads to \u003Cstrong\u003Eulnar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E entrapment. The characteristic \u0027claw hand\u0027 deformity occurs due to paralysis of the intrinsic hand muscles (including third and fourth lumbricals), resulting in unopposed action of the long flexors and extensors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E injury typically presents with wrist drop and loss of sensation over the anatomical snuffbox and dorsal first web space. It is commonly injured in spiral fractures of the humeral shaft.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedian nerve\u003C/strong\u003E injury results in different patterns depending on the level of injury. High lesions cause the \u0027hand of benediction\u0027 sign with inability to flex the index and middle fingers, while low lesions lead to thenar wasting and the \u0027ape hand\u0027 deformity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior interosseous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is a pure motor branch of the median nerve. Its injury causes weakness of the flexor pollicis longus and flexor digitorum profundus to the index finger, resulting in inability to form an \u0027OK\u0027 sign.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior interosseous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is a motor branch of the radial nerve. Its injury causes weakness of digit extension at the metacarpophalangeal joints and thumb abduction, but wrist extension is preserved as it branches distal to the extensor carpi radialis. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ulnar nerve injury classically presents with clawing of the ring and little fingers due to weakness of intrinsic hand muscles.","Previous medial epicondyle injury is a risk factor for ulnar nerve entrapment.","Ulnar nerve symptoms include weakness of grip, sensory changes in the little finger, and difficulty with fine motor tasks."],"references":["Lane R, Nallamothu SV. Claw Hand. [Updated 2022 Apr 30]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. FL USA: StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507781/","Orthobullets. Intrinsic minus hand {Claw Hand) [Internet]. Pasadena CA USA. 2021 May 18. Available from: https://www.orthobullets.com/hand/6010/intrinsic-minus-hand-claw-hand"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62391"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"869"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17091"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17091"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/17efe154-84a8-4818-aa33-9c127adaf4bd.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/17efe154-84a8-4818-aa33-9c127adaf4bd.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":380}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62391"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T15:57:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T15:57:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{